TY  - JOUR
T1  - Do I Follow My Friends or the Crowd? Information Cascades in Online Movie Ratings
AU  - Lee, Young-Jin
AU  - Hosanagar, Kartik
AU  - Tan, Yong
Y1  - 2015/04/15
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2015/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2014.2082
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2014.2082
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2241
EP  - 2258
VL  - 61
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Online product ratings are widely available on the Internet and are known to influence prospective buyers. An emerging literature has started to look at how ratings are generated and, in particular, how they are influenced by prior ratings. We study the social influence of prior ratings and, in particular, investigate any differential impact of prior ratings by strangers (?crowd?) versus friends. We find evidence of both herding and differentiation behavior in crowd ratings wherein users? ratings are influenced positively or negatively by prior ratings depending on movie popularity. In contrast, friends? ratings always induce herding. Further, the presence of social networking reduces the likelihood of herding on prior ratings by the crowd. Finally, we find that an increase in the number of friends who can potentially observe a user?s rating (?audience size?) has a positive impact on ratings. These findings raise questions about the reliability of ratings as unbiased indicators of quality and advocate the need for techniques to debias rating systems. This paper was accepted by Sandra Slaughter, information systems.
AB  - Online product ratings are widely available on the Internet and are known to influence prospective buyers. An emerging literature has started to look at how ratings are generated and, in particular, how they are influenced by prior ratings. We study the social influence of prior ratings and, in particular, investigate any differential impact of prior ratings by strangers (?crowd?) versus friends. We find evidence of both herding and differentiation behavior in crowd ratings wherein users? ratings are influenced positively or negatively by prior ratings depending on movie popularity. In contrast, friends? ratings always induce herding. Further, the presence of social networking reduces the likelihood of herding on prior ratings by the crowd. Finally, we find that an increase in the number of friends who can potentially observe a user?s rating (?audience size?) has a positive impact on ratings. These findings raise questions about the reliability of ratings as unbiased indicators of quality and advocate the need for techniques to debias rating systems. This paper was accepted by Sandra Slaughter, information systems.
